commitResults.messageTitle: Merge branch 'branch-A-JavaDoc' of github.com:wenruu/ip into branch-A-JavaDoc
commitResults.messageBody:
* 'branch-A-JavaDoc' of github.com:wenruu/ip:
  Add JavaDocs to more classes

Code previously was not adherent to the code style guidelines of CS2103T.

This has been fixed using CheckStyle.

Botato was only text-based, making the user experience less than ideal.

Adding a GUI makes using the chatbot more intuitive and aesthetically
pleasing.

Integrating JavaFX, and using FXML files to define the user interface
along with CSS stylesheets allows us to create a beautiful, easily
editable GUI.

Integrating JavaFX allows us to create a GUI. Using FXML lets us use
SceneBuilder to edit the GUI layout graphically instead of
programatically. Adding CSS stylesheets lets us easily style and edit
the design of the GUI. For example, with SceneBuilder, we can tweak the
design and immediately see the changes without having to run the
application.

Let's further customise the design by,
* Adding a custom background to the chat
* Tweaking the designs and colours of the application
* Add more functionalities to the application

Validating task numbers is handled in the commands that use them.

This causes unnecessary code duplication and reduces code clarity.

Let's validate task numbers in the parser instead.

This makes behaviour clearer and reduces code duplication.

Furthermore, assertions were added to commands using task numbers to
ensure task numbers are valid and prevent null pointer errors.
Refactor parser, add asserts
A-CodeQuality

Background was clashing with other UI design elements, making it hard
to see the dialog boxes and profile pictures.

This negatively impacts the user experience.

Reducing the background image transparency to 30 makes other UI elements
much clearer while keeping the image discernible compared to blurring.

In addition, background image was shifted to the correct directory in
resources, under "images" now.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add custom background to user guide
Adjust font and dialog box colours
commitResults.messageBody:
Design for both user and botato dialog boxes is exactly the same, with a
gradient.

This makes it often confusing who's who and the gradient can make words
harder to discern sometimes.

Changing each the user's and botato's dialog boxes to different
monotonous colours makes who's saying what clearer. Changing botato's
font colour to a lighter one makes it easier to read.

Botato was given the lighter shade because it feels more intuitive that
the user's dialog box is darker than the person replying. Making
colours monotonous allows us to optimise text to give a higher contrast,
making both dialog boxes more readable.

Help functionality is purely text-based and unintuitive, with no
examples shown to the user.

This makes the help not very helpful, and users may have to keep
scrolling up and down to copy and find the information they need.

Let's make the app open a new window containing the user guide when
the user asks for help.

As we already have a polished user guide (README.md), it would be
easier and better to just reuse that for the internal help function,
as updating the guide as more functionalities are added is much easier
this way. In addition, the user may be using the app offline, so just
opening the app's website is not good.

A new dependency, FlexMark, was added to convert .md to HTML (as JavaFX
does not natively support reading .md files), and the HTML file is
opened in a new WebView using JavaFX.

In addition, updated the parser to read user inputs for single-word
commands (help, list etc) even if there are leading or trailing
whitespaces, in the spirit of fat fingers.

Let's,
* Make sure the new dependency is properly bundled into the .jar file
  when running shadowJar
* Test that the user guide opens correctly in other systems
